==== (3) New Jersey Devils vs. (6) Carolina Hurricanes ====
The New Jersey Devils entered the playoffs as the third seed in the Eastern Conference after winning the Atlantic Division with 106 points. The Carolina Hurricanes earned the sixth seed with 97 points.

New Jersey won Game 1 with goaltender [[Martin Brodeur]] stopping 18 of 19 shots and the Devils' top line playing phenomenally, with [[Zach Parise]] and [[Patrik Elias]] coming up with goals. .<ref>{{cite web |title= Devils 4, Hurricanes 1 |first= Brian |last= Compton |url= http://www.nhl.com/ice/recap.htm?id=2008030131 |date= 15 April 2009 |publisher= NHL.com |accessdate= 17 May 2009 }}</ref> In Game 2, [[Tim Gleason]] scored 2:40 into overtime for his first goal of the season to give Carolina a 2–1 victory. The game was a goaltending battle that saw Brodeur and [[Cam Ward]] each stop over 30 shots<ref>{{cite web |title= Gleason's OT goal lifts 'Canes over Devils |first= Brian |last= Compton |url= http://www.nhl.com/ice/recap.htm?id=2008030132 |date= 17 April 2009 |publisher= NHL.com |accessdate= 17 May 2009 }}</ref> Game 3 also went into overtime, but this time the Devils prevailed, 3–2, with [[Travis Zajac]] scoring at 4:48 into the extra period.<ref>{{cite web |title= Zajac's OT winner gives Devils edge |first= Brian |last= Compton |url= http://www.nhl.com/ice/recap.htm?id=2008030133 |date= 19 April 2009 |publisher= NHL.com |accessdate= 17 May 2009 }}</ref> It appeared that Game 4 would also go into overtime, but it ended with an epic conclusion. Carolina led 3-0, but New Jersey rallied to tie the game in the third. [[Jussi Jokinen]] proved to be the hero, as he scored on a deflection with 0.2 seconds of regulation to give the Hurricanes a 4–3 victory.<ref>{{cite web |title= Hurricanes shock Devils 4-3 with late goal |first= Brian |last= Compton |url= http://www.nhl.com/ice/recap.htm?id=2008030134 |date= 21 April 2009 |publisher= NHL.com |accessdate= 17 May 2009 }}</ref> This goal was the latest game winning regulation goal in Stanley Cup Playoff history.<ref>{{cite web |title= Wild finish has Devils, 'Canes all tied up  |first= Brian |last= Compton |url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=419533&navid=DL|NHL|Home|title|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5j2MbfIgA|archivedate=2009-08-14|deadurl=no|accessdate=2009-06-15}}</ref> The next two games of the series were shutouts: Brodeur stopped 44 shots in a 1–0 victory for the Devils in Game 5 (with [[David Clarkson (ice hockey)|David Clarkson]] providing the game's sole goal),<ref>{{cite web |title= Brodeur's gem gives Devils 1-0 win over 'Canes |first= Brian |last= Compton |url= http://www.nhl.com/ice/recap.htm?id=2008030135 |date= 23 April 2009 |publisher= NHL.com |accessdate= 17 May 2009 }}</ref> while [[Cam Ward]] stopped 28 shots and [[Eric Staal]] scored twice in a 4–0 victory for Carolina in Game 6.<ref>{{cite web |title= Hurricanes blank Devils, series goes distance |first= Brian |last= Compton |url= http://www.nhl.com/ice/recap.htm?id=2008030136 |date= 26 April 2009 |publisher= NHL.com |accessdate= 17 May 2009 }}</ref> The Hurricanes were behind for much of Game 7 but scored two goals inside the last 1:20 of the third period, one by Jokinen and the other by Staal, to win the contest, 4–3, and eliminate the Devils.<ref>{{cite web |title= Hurricanes stun Devils to win game 7 |first= Brian |last= Compton |url= http://www.nhl.com/ice/recap.htm?id=2008030137 |date= 28 April 2009 |publisher= NHL.com |accessdate= 17 May 2009 }}</ref>

