==== (4) Pittsburgh Penguins vs. (5) Philadelphia Flyers ====
The Pittsburgh Penguins and Philadelphia Flyers qualified for the playoffs as the fourth and fifth seeds in the Eastern Conference, respectively. Both finished the regular season with 99 points, but the Penguins won the tiebreaker based on total wins (45 to 44). The Penguins and Flyers had previously met in the previous season's Eastern Conference Finals, with the Penguins winning 4-1. It was the Penguins first win against the Flyers, having lost against them in three previous series ([[1989_Stanley_Cup_playoffs#Division_finals|1989]], [[1997 Stanley Cup playoffs|1997]] and [[2000 Stanley Cup playoffs|2000]]).

Pittsburgh won the series over Philadelphia, four games to two. [[Sidney Crosby]] scored a power play goal early in the first period of Game 1, sparking the Penguins to a 4–1 win against an undisciplined Flyers team that took 12 penalties.<ref>{{cite web |title= Penguins 4, Flyers 1 |first= Adam |last= Kimelman |url= http://www.nhl.com/ice/recap.htm?id=2008030141 |date= 15 April 2009 |publisher= NHL.com |accessdate= 26 April 2009 }}</ref> In Game 2, [[Bill Guerin]] scored two goals including the game-winner during a five-on-three power play at 18:29 in overtime to give Pittsburgh a 3–2 victory.<ref>{{cite web |title= Penguins top Flyers on Guerin's OT goal |first= Adam |last= Kimelman |url= http://www.nhl.com/ice/recap.htm?id=2008030142 |date= 17 April 2009 |publisher= NHL.com |accessdate= 26 April 2009 }}</ref> The Flyers bounced back in Game 3 with a 6–3 victory that featured two goals by [[Simon Gagne]].<ref>{{cite web |title= Giroux, Flyers bounce back with big effort |first= Adam |last= Kimelman |url= http://www.nhl.com/ice/recap.htm?id=2008030143 |date= 19 April 2009 |publisher= NHL.com |accessdate= 17 May 2009 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5j2Ma2MFd|archivedate=2009-08-14|deadurl=no}}</ref> Pittsburgh goaltender [[Marc-André Fleury]] stopped 45 shots and helped kill off nine Philadelphia power plays, while [[Tyler Kennedy]] scored the game winner, to give Pittsburgh a 3–1 win in Game 4.<ref>{{cite web |title= Fleury steals one for Penguins |first= Adam |last= Kimelman |url= http://www.nhl.com/ice/recap.htm?id=2008030144 |date= 21 April 2009 |publisher= NHL.com |accessdate= 26 April 2009 }}</ref> Flyers goaltender [[Martin Biron]] stopped all 28 shots, and Philadelphia got scoring from unlikely sources such as [[Arron Asham]], to give the Flyers a 3–0 victory in Game 5.<ref>{{cite web |title= Flyers blank Penguins 3-0 to force Game 6 |first= Adam |last= Kimelman |url= http://www.nhl.com/ice/recap.htm?id=2008030145 |date= 23 April 2009 |publisher= NHL.com |accessdate= 26 April 2009 }}</ref> Then in Game 6, Philadelphia jumped to a 3–0 lead in the second period and appeared to be on their way to force a Game 7. However, a fight between Philadelphia's [[Daniel Carcillo]] and Pittsburgh's [[Max Talbot]] reenergized the Penguins, who erupted to score five unanswered goals, including two by Crosby, to win the game and the series.<ref>{{cite web |title= Penguins' rally eliminates Flyers from playoffs |first= Adam |last= Kimelman |url= http://www.nhl.com/ice/recap.htm?id=2008030146 |date= 25 April 2009 |publisher= NHL.com |accessdate= 26 April 2009 }}</ref>

