== Conference Semi-finals ==
For the first time since the [[2001 Stanley Cup playoffs|2001 playoffs]], at least three Conference semi-final series  extended to seven games.<ref>{{cite web |title= Conference Semifinals peak with three Game 7s |url= http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=422638 |date= 13 May 2009 |publisher= NHL.com |accessdate= 14 May 2009 }}</ref>

=== Eastern Conference Semi-finals ===
==== (1) Boston Bruins vs. (6) Carolina Hurricanes ====
The Carolina Hurricanes eliminated the Boston Bruins in seven games to advance to their first Eastern Conference Final since their Cup championship season in [[2006 Stanley Cup playoffs|2006]]. [[Marc Savard]] scored two goals to help give the Bruins a 4–1 victory in Game 1,<ref>{{cite web |title= Bruins 4, Hurricanes 1 |first= Shawn P. |last= Roarke |url= http://www.nhl.com/ice/recap.htm?id=2008030211 |date= 1 May 2009 |publisher= NHL.com |accessdate= 15 May 2009 }}</ref> but the Hurricanes won the next three games of the series. First, Carolina goaltender [[Cam Ward]] stopped all 36 shots and [[Matt Cullen]] provided a shorthanded marker in a 3–0 victory in Game 2.<ref>{{cite web |title= No longer perfect, Bruins fall to 'Canes |first= Shawn P. |last= Roarke |url= http://www.nhl.com/ice/recap.htm?id=2008030212 |date= 3 May 2009 |publisher= NHL.com |accessdate= 15 May 2009 }}</ref> Next, [[Jussi Jokinen]] scored at 2:48 into overtime of Game 3 to give the Hurricanes a 3–2 victory.<ref>{{cite web |title= Jokinen's OT goal lifts Carolina over Boston |first= Shawn P. |last= Roarke |url= http://www.nhl.com/ice/recap.htm?id=2008030213 |date= 6 May 2009 |publisher= NHL.com |accessdate= 15 May 2009 }}</ref> In Game 4, [[Eric Staal]] scored two goals and Ward stopped 18 out of only 19 shots en route to a 4–1 victory.<ref>{{cite web |title= Jokinen, Staal stake 'Canes to 3-1 series lead |first= Shawn P. |last= Roarke |url= http://www.nhl.com/ice/recap.htm?id=2008030214 |date= 8 May 2009 |publisher= NHL.com |accessdate= 15 May 2009 }}</ref> However, [[Phil Kessel]] scored two goals and goaltender [[Tim Thomas (ice hockey)|Tim Thomas]] stopped all 19 shots to give Boston a 4–0 victory in Game 5.<ref>{{cite web |title= Bruins blank 'Canes, cut series deficit to 3-2 |first= Shawn P. |last= Roarke |url= http://www.nhl.com/ice/recap.htm?id=2008030215 |date= 10 May 2009 |publisher= NHL.com |accessdate= 15 May 2009 }}</ref> Thomas then stopped 31 out of 33 shots and [[Mark Recchi]] provided an early game winner to help the Bruins win 4–2 in Game 6.<ref>{{cite web |title= Bruins even series with 4-2 victory over Hurricanes |first= Shawn P. |last= Roarke |url= http://www.nhl.com/ice/recap.htm?id=2008030216 |date= 12 May 2009 |publisher= NHL.com |accessdate= 17 May 2009 }}</ref> The Hurricanes led Game 7 after two periods, but [[Milan Lucic]] tied the game at 6:19 in the third. However, [[Scott Walker (ice hockey)|Scott Walker]] scored the game-winning goal at 18:46 into the first overtime period to give the Hurricanes a 3–2 victory and the series.<ref>{{cite web |title= Walker's OT goal lifts 'Canes into East final |first= Shawn P. |last= Roarke |url= http://www.nhl.com/ice/recap.htm?id=2008030217 |date= 14 May 2009 |publisher= NHL.com |accessdate= 17 May 2009 }}</ref>

